06274nam a22010935i 9780691203645DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2019043720  a97806912036457 a10.1515/97806912036452doi  a(DE-B1597)546363  a(OCoLC)1143815921  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aJF1083 4aJF1083b.B58 2021 7aPOL0080002bisacsh04a364.13242231 aBirch, Sarah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aElectoral Violence, Corruption, and Political Order /cSarah Birch. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b12 b/w illus. 13 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tPREFACE AND ACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Carrots and Sticks -- t3. Coercive Electoral Governance -- t4. Violence by Nonstate Actors -- t5. Divergent Contexts and Patterns of Violent Elections -- t6. Strategies of Electoral-Violence Prevention -- t7. Conclusion. IMPLICATIONS FOR THEORY, POL ICY, AND PRACTICE -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX -- tA NOTE ON THE TYPE0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA comprehensive look at how violence has been used to manipulate competitive electoral processes around the world since World War IIThroughout their history, political elections have been threatened by conflict, and the use of force has in the past several decades been an integral part of electoral processes in a significant number of contemporary states. However, the study of elections has yet to produce a comprehensive account of electoral violence. Drawing on cross-national datasets together with fourteen detailed case studies from around the world, Electoral Violence, Corruption, and Political Order offers a global comparative analysis of violent electoral practices since the Second World War.Sarah Birch shows that the way power is structured in society largely explains why elections are at risk of violence in some contexts but not in others. Countries with high levels of corruption and weak democratic institutions are especially vulnerable to disruptions of electoral peace. She examines how corrupt actors use violence to back up other forms of electoral manipulation, including vote buying and ballot stuffing. In addition to investigating why electoral violence takes place, Birch considers what can be done to prevent it in the future, arguing that electoral authority and the quality of electoral governance is more important than the formal design of electoral institutions.Delving into a deeply influential aspect of political malpractice, Electoral Violence, Corruption, and Political Order explores the circumstances in which individuals choose to employ violence as an electoral strategy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aElectionsxCorrupt practices. 0aPolitical corruption. 0aPolitical violence. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Campaigns & Elections.2bisacsh  aContentious Elections: From Ballots to Barricades.  aDavid Gillies.  aDorina Bekoe.  aElecting Peace: Violence Prevention and Impact at the Polls.  aElections in Dangerous Places: Democracy and the Paradoxes of Peacebuilding.  aElectoral Violence in Sub-Saharan Africa.  aFerran Martínez i Coma.  aInken Von Borzyskowski.  aJesper Bjarnesen.  aJonas Claes.  aKovacs Söderberg.  aMimmi Bjarnesen.  aPippa Norris.  aRichard Frank.  aStephanie Burchard.  aThe Credibility Challenge: How Democracy Aid Influences Election Violence.  aViolence in African Elections: Between Democracy and Big Man Politics.  aVoting in Fear.  aconduct.  aethics.  afairness.  afraud.  aimpropriety.  aintegrity.  